< -- ImpCEvalFun: An Evaluation Function for Imp
< 
< -- We saw in the Imp chapter how a naive approach to defining a
< -- function representing evaluation for Imp runs into difficulties.
< -- There, we adopted the solution of changing from a functional to a
< -- relational definition of evaluation.  In this optional chapter, we
< -- consider strategies for getting the functional approach to work.
< 
< -- ####################################
< -- * A Broken Evaluator
< -- TERSE: HIDEFROMHTML
< import Imp
< import Maps
< -- TERSE: /HIDEFROMHTML
< 
< open AExp BExp Com
< 
< -- Here was our first try at an evaluation function for commands,
< -- omitting `while`.
< 
< def cevalStep1 (st : State) (c : Com) : State :=
<   match c with
<   | CSkip =>
<       st
<   | CAsgn l a1 =>
<       (l !-> aeval st a1 ; st)
<   | CSeq c1 c2 =>
<       let st' := cevalStep1 st c1
<       cevalStep1 st' c2
<   | CIf b c1 c2 =>
<       if (beval st b)
<         then cevalStep1 st c1
<         else cevalStep1 st c2
<   | CWhile _ _ =>
<       st  -- bogus
< 
< -- ***
< -- As we remarked in chapter Imp, in a traditional functional
< -- programming language like ML or Haskell we could write the while
< -- case as follows:
< --
< --     | CWhile b1 c1 =>
< --         if (beval st b1) then
< --           cevalStep1 st (CSeq c1 (CWhile b1 c1))
< --         else st
< --
< -- Lean doesn't accept such a definition because the function we want
< -- to define is not guaranteed to terminate. Indeed, the changed
< -- `cevalStep1` function applied to the `loop` program from `Imp.lean`
< -- would never terminate. Since Lean is not just a functional
< -- programming language but also a consistent logic, any potentially
< -- non-terminating function needs to be rejected (unless we use
< -- `partial`).  Here is an invalid Lean program showing what would go
< -- wrong if Lean allowed non-terminating recursive functions:
< --
< --     def loopFalse (n : Nat) : False := loopFalse n
< --
< -- That is, propositions like `False` would become provable (e.g.,
< -- `loopFalse 0` would be a proof of `False`), which would be a
< -- disaster for Lean's logical consistency.
< --
< -- Thus, because it doesn't terminate on all inputs, the full version
< -- of `cevalStep1` cannot be written as a total function in Lean -- at
< -- least not without one additional trick...
< --
< -- Note: Lean does offer `partial def`, which allows non-terminating
< -- functions. However, a `partial def` cannot be used in proofs (it is
< -- opaque), so it is not useful when we want to reason about the
< -- evaluator. We show a `partial def` version below for illustration.
< 
< -- Here is an evaluator using `partial def` that actually handles while
< -- loops, but cannot be unfolded in proofs:
< 
< partial def cevalPartial (st : State) (c : Com) : State :=
<   match c with
<   | CSkip => st
<   | CAsgn l a1 => (l !-> aeval st a1 ; st)
<   | CSeq c1 c2 =>
<       let st' := cevalPartial st c1
<       cevalPartial st' c2
<   | CIf b c1 c2 =>
<       if beval st b then cevalPartial st c1
<       else cevalPartial st c2
<   | CWhile b c1 =>
<       if beval st b then
<         let st' := cevalPartial st c1
<         cevalPartial st' (CWhile b c1)
<       else st
< 
< -- ####################################
< -- * A Step-Indexed Evaluator
< 
< -- The trick we need is to pass an _additional_ parameter to the
< -- evaluation function that tells it how long to run.  Informally, we
< -- start the evaluator with a certain amount of "gas" in its tank,
< -- and we allow it to run until either it terminates in the usual way
< -- _or_ it runs out of gas, at which point we simply stop evaluating
< -- and say that the final result is the empty memory.  (We could also
< -- say that the result is the current state at the point where the
< -- evaluator runs out of gas -- it doesn't really matter because the
< -- result is going to be wrong in either case!)
< 
< def cevalStep2 (st : State) (c : Com) (i : Nat) : State :=
<   match i with
<   | 0 => empty_st
<   | i' + 1 =>
<     match c with
<     | CSkip =>
<         st
<     | CAsgn l a1 =>
<         (l !-> aeval st a1 ; st)
<     | CSeq c1 c2 =>
<         let st' := cevalStep2 st c1 i'
<         cevalStep2 st' c2 i'
<     | CIf b c1 c2 =>
<         if (beval st b)
<           then cevalStep2 st c1 i'
<           else cevalStep2 st c2 i'
<     | CWhile b1 c1 =>
<         if (beval st b1)
<         then let st' := cevalStep2 st c1 i'
<              cevalStep2 st' c i'
<         else st
< 
< -- FULL: _Note_: It is tempting to think that the index `i` here is
< -- counting the "number of steps of evaluation."  But if you look
< -- closely you'll see that this is not the case: for example, in the
< -- rule for sequencing, the same `i` is passed to both recursive
< -- calls.  Understanding the exact way that `i` is treated will be
< -- important in the proof of `ceval__ceval_step`, which is given as
< -- an exercise below.
< --
< -- One thing that is not so nice about this evaluator is that we
< -- can't tell, from its result, whether it stopped because the
< -- program terminated normally or because it ran out of gas.  Our
< -- next version returns an `Option State` instead of just a `State`,
< -- so that we can distinguish between normal and abnormal
< -- termination.
< 
< def cevalStep3 (st : State) (c : Com) (i : Nat)
<                     : Option State :=
<   match i with
<   | 0 => none
<   | i' + 1 =>
<     match c with
<     | CSkip =>
<         some st
<     | CAsgn l a1 =>
<         some (l !-> aeval st a1 ; st)
<     | CSeq c1 c2 =>
<         match (cevalStep3 st c1 i') with
<         | some st' => cevalStep3 st' c2 i'
<         | none => none
<     | CIf b c1 c2 =>
<         if (beval st b)
<           then cevalStep3 st c1 i'
<           else cevalStep3 st c2 i'
<     | CWhile b1 c1 =>
<         if (beval st b1)
<         then match (cevalStep3 st c1 i') with
<              | some st' => cevalStep3 st' c i'
<              | none => none
<         else some st
< 
< -- We can improve the readability of this version by using Lean's
< -- monadic `do` notation (or `>>=`/`bind`) to hide the plumbing
< -- involved in repeatedly matching against optional states.
< -- In Lean, `Option` is a monad, so we can use `do` notation directly.
< -- However, for ease of reasoning we keep the explicit match version
< -- as our canonical definition.
< 
< def cevalStep (st : State) (c : Com) (i : Nat)
<                     : Option State :=
<   match i with
<   | 0 => none
<   | i' + 1 =>
<     match c with
<     | CSkip =>
<         some st
<     | CAsgn l a1 =>
<         some (l !-> aeval st a1 ; st)
<     | CSeq c1 c2 =>
<         match cevalStep st c1 i' with
<         | some st' => cevalStep st' c2 i'
<         | none => none
<     | CIf b c1 c2 =>
<         if (beval st b)
<           then cevalStep st c1 i'
<           else cevalStep st c2 i'
<     | CWhile b1 c1 =>
<         if (beval st b1)
<         then match cevalStep st c1 i' with
<              | some st' => cevalStep st' c i'
<              | none => none
<         else some st
< 
< def testCeval (st : State) (c : Com) : Option (Nat × Nat × Nat) :=
<   match cevalStep st c 500 with
<   | none    => none
<   | some st => some (st X, st Y, st Z)
< 
< -- example_test_ceval
< example :
<      testCeval empty_st
<        (CSeq (CAsgn X (ANum 2))
<              (CIf (BLe (AId X) (ANum 1))
<                   (CAsgn Y (ANum 3))
<                   (CAsgn Z (ANum 4))))
<      = some (2, 0, 4) := by rfl
< 
